New English name: Largehead Anchovy (
Figs. 1
–5;
Tables 1–3
)

Distribution.
Currently known only from the southern Red Sea (off 
Djibouti
) and the Arabian Sea (off the 
Sultanate of Oman
).

Encrasicholina macrocephala
is easily distinguished from
E. punctifer Fowler 1938
[with
Stolephorus buccaneeri
Strasburg, 1960
, a junior synonym (
Wongratana 1983
;
Whitehead et al. 1988
;
Wongratana et al. 1999
).],
E. oligobranchus (
Wongratana 1983
)
, and
E. purpurea (Fowler 1900 )
by its long upper jaw, with posterior tip extending beyond the posterior margin of the preopercle (vs. posterior tip of upper jaw not reaching to posterior margin of preopercle in the other three species;
Strasburg 1960
;
Whitehead et al . 1988
;
Wongratana et al . 1999
).
Encrasicholina macrocephala
also differs from
E. oligobranchus
by having more gill rakers [gill rakers on 1 st arch 17–20 (modally 19 ) in upper series, 21–25 ( 23 ) in lower series vs. 13 –14, 17– 18 , respectively;
Wongratana 1983
;
Whitehead et al . 1988
;
Wongratana et al . 1999
]. The new species differs from
S. pseudoheterolobus Hardenberg 1933
[regarded as a junior synonym of
E. heteroloba (Rüppell 1837 )
;
Whitehead et al . 1988
;
Wongratana et al . 1999
] by having a larger head [head length 29.5–31.7 % of SL (mean 30.4 %) vs. 23.8–26.3 % in syntypes of
S. pseudoheterolobus
;
Hardenberg, 1933 a
, b ,
1934
]. Although most meristic characters of
E. macrocephala
agree well with those of
E. heteroloba
, the former differs in having three unbranched rays in the dorsal and anal fins [vs. 2 or rarely 1 unbranched ray;
Whitehead et al . 1988
;
Wongratana et al. 1999
;
Hata et al . 2012
; this study].
